ull Run, the similarities between the colors of the Union and Confederate uniforms created concern over what later would be called 'friendly fire' and helped decide the outcome of the first major battle. He evokes what it might have felt like to be in the HL Hunley submarine, in which eight men worked in darkness in a space 48 inches high, 42 inches wide. Often argued to be the first 'total war,' the Civil War overwhelmed the senses because of its unprecedented nature and scope, rendering sight less reliable and engaging the nonvisual senses. Sherman's March was little less than a full-blown assault on Southern sense and sensibility, leaving nothing untouched. The Smell of Battle, The Taste of Siege offers readers a way to experience of the Civil War with fresh eyes"--Provided by publisher.  a29 0aSenses and sensationzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aUnited StatesxHistoryyCivil War, 1861-1865xSocial aspects. 0aUnited StatesxHistoryyCivil War, 1861-1865xPsychological aspects. 0aUnited StatesxHistoryyCivil War, 1861-1865vPersonal narratives.  aE468.9 .S654 2015hGMCT-OS-Bi1007401555p34.09kAVAIL_SOON  aE468.9 .S654 2015wLCc1i1007401555d3/12/2015lON_SHELFmGR_MACEWANp$34.09rYsYtBOOKu3/3/201501ahttp://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n97015190bhttp://viaf.org/viaf/35634283